The paper focuses on training a humanoid robot to play games using deep learning techniques, which falls under the category of robotics (cs.RO) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The approach also heavily relies on visual perception and tracking, which suggests computer vision (cs.CV) as another likely sub-category. The paper also involves human-robot interaction and user evaluation, which could fall under human-computer interaction (cs.HC). Finally, the paper proposes novel algorithms for policy learning, which is a sub-field of machine learning (cs.LG).
